[[Image:Aufeis close.jpg|thumb|upright|Laminations of ice in a sheet of aufeis]] '''Aufeis''', ({{IPAc-en|ˈ|aʊ|f|aɪ|s}} {{respell|OW|fyse}}), ([[German language|German]] for "ice on top") is a sheet-like mass of layered [[ice]] that forms from successive flows of ground water during freezing temperatures. This form of ice is also called '''overflow''', '''icings''', or the [[Russian language|Russian]] term, '''naled'''. The term was first used in 1859 by A. T. von Middendorff following his observations of the phenomenon in northern [[Siberia]].<ref name="Ashton">Ashton, George D. 1986. River and lake ice engineering. Chelsea, Michigan, USA: Book Crafters, Inc.</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Leffingwell |first=Ernest de K. |date=1919 |title=The Canning River region, northern Alaska |publisher=[[U.S. Geological Survey]] |volume=Professional Paper 109 |p=158 |url=http://pubs.usgs.gov/pp/0109/report.pdf}}</ref>
==Formation== [[Image:Aufeis far.jpg|thumb|upright=1.15|A sheet of aufeis in a glacial valley in Mongolia]] Aufeis accumulates during winter along [[stream]] and [[river]] [[valley]]s in [[arctic]] and [[subarctic]] environments. It forms by upwelling of river water behind [[Ice jam|ice dam]]s, or by ground-water discharge. The latter mechanism prevails in high-gradient [[alpine climate|alpine]] streams as they [[freezing|freeze]] solid. Ground-water discharge is blocked by ice, perturbing the steady-state condition and causing a small incremental rise in the local [[water table]] until discharge occurs along the bank and over the top of the previously formed ice. Successive ice layers can lead to aufeis accumulations that are several meters thick. Aufeis typically melts out during summer and will often form in the same place year after year.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Hu |first1=Xiaogang |last2=Pollard |first2=Wayne H. |date=September 1997 |title=The Hydrologic Analysis and Modeling of River Icing Growth, North Fork Pass, Yukon Territory, Canada |journal=[[Permafrost and Periglacial Processes]] |publisher=[[John Wiley & Sons]] |volume=8 |issue=3 |pages=279–294 |doi=10.1002/(SICI)1099-1530(199709)8:3<279::AID-PPP260>3.0.CO;2-7 |url=http://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/10.1002/(SICI)1099-1530(199709)8:3%3C279::AID-PPP260%3E3.0.CO;2-7/pdf |subscription=yes}}</ref>
==Impact== [[File:Aufeis in the Brooks Range of Alaska.JPG|thumb|left|Backpackers cross a sheet of aufeis in the [[Anaktuvuk River]] Valley of Alaska]] Sheets of aufeis may block stream channels and cause their [[flood plains]] to widen as spring floodwaters are forced to flow around the ice.<ref name=Harden>{{cite journal |last1=Harden |first1=Deborah |last2=Barnes |first2=Peter |last3=Reimnitz |first3=Erk |date=1977 |title=Distribution and character of naleds in northeastern Alaska |journal=Arctic |volume=30 |issue=1 |pp=28–40 |url=http://arctic.journalhosting.ucalgary.ca/arctic/index.php/arctic/article/download/2681/2658 |doi=10.14430/arctic2681}}</ref> Research on aufeis has to a large extent been motivated by the variety of engineering problems the ice sheets can cause (e.g. blocking drainages and causing flooding of roads).<ref name=Kane>{{cite journal |last1=Kane |first1=Douglas L. |date=1981 |title=Physical mechanics of aufeis growth |journal=Canadian Journal of Civil Engineering |volume=8 |issue=2 |pages=186–195 |url=http://www.nrcresearchpress.com/doi/pdf/10.1139/l81-026 |doi=10.1139/l81-026}}</ref> [[Culvert]]s and pipelines can actually help to block flow and lead to the development of more extensive aufeis.<ref>Williams and Smith{{Citation needed|date=October 2015}}</ref>
Aufeis can present an extreme danger to recreational boaters even during summer months, who can find themselves trapped between walls of ice or pulled under aufeis by the current of the river. Breaking dams of aufeis can also cause flash floods downriver.<ref>{{cite web |work=Alaska.org |title=Dangers of Aufeis on Alaskan Rivers |url=http://www.alaska.org/advice/aufeis-on-the-alaskan-rivers |accessdate=21 November 2013}}</ref> Proper scouting and precautions when choosing campsites can minimize these risks {{Citation needed|reason=appears to be original research|date=June 2017}}.
===City cooling=== In late 2011, Mongolia planned to test the use and storage of artificial naleds as a way of cooling [[Ulan Bator]] in the hot Mongolian summer, and reducing the use of energy-intensive [[air conditioning]].<ref>{{cite news |first=Jonathan |last=Watts |title=Mongolia bids to keep city cool with 'ice shield' experiment |work=[[The Guardian]] |date=15 November 2011|url=https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2011/nov/15/mongolia-ice-shield-geoengineering}}</ref>
==Occurrence== Sheets of aufeis have been observed in [[Alaska]],<ref name=Harden/><ref name=Kane/> Arctic [[Canada]],<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Veillette |first1=J.J. |last2=Thomas |first2=R.D. |date=November 1979 |title=Icings and seepage in frozen glacio-fluvial deposits, District of Keewatin, NWT |journal=Canadian Geotechnical Journal |volume=16 |issue=4 |pages=789–798 |url=http://www.nrcresearchpress.com/doi/pdf/10.1139/t79-084 |doi=10.1139/t79-084}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Reedyk |first1=Sharon |last2=Woo |first2=Ming-Ko |last3=Prowse |first3=Terry D. |date=1995 |title=Contribution of icing ablation to streamflow in a discontinuous permafrost area: |journal=Canadian Journal of Earth Sciences |volume=32 |issue=1 |pages=13–20 |url=http://www.nrcresearchpress.com/doi/pdf/10.1139/e95-002 |doi=10.1139/e95-002|bibcode=1995CaJES..32...13R }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last=Clark |first=Ian D. |last2=Lauriol |first2=Bernard |date=1997 |title=Aufeis of the Firth River Basin, Northern Yukon, Canada: Insights into Permafrost Hydrogeology and Karst |journal=Arctic and Alpine Research |publisher=INSTAAR, University of Colorado |volume=29 |issue=2 |pages=240–252 |doi=10.2307/1552053 |jstor=1552053 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Priesnitz |first1=Kuno |last2=Schunke |first2=Ekkehard |date=2002 |title=The fluvial morphodynamics of two small permafrost drainage basins, northwestern Canada |journal=Permafrost and Periglacial Processes |publisher=John Wiley & Sons |volume=13 |issue=3 |pages=207–217 |url=http://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/10.1002/ppp.424/pdf |doi=10.1002/ppp.424 |subscription=yes}}</ref> [[Russia]],<ref>{{cite book |last1=Alekseev |first1=V. |last2=Savko |first2=N. |date=1975 |title=The theory of naled processes |publisher=Nayka |pp=1–205}}</ref><ref>{{cite conference |last1=Sokolov |first1=B. L. |date=1978 |title=Regime of Naleds |work=USSR Contribution, Permafrost: Second International Conference |publisher=[[National Academy of Sciences]] |editor-first=Frederick J. |editor-last=Sanger |pp=408–411 |url={{google books||plainurl=yes|page=408}} |isbn=0-309-02746-2}}</ref> and [[Mongolia]].<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Froehlich |first1=Wojciech |last2=Slupik |first2=January |date=1982 |title=River icings and fluvial activity in extreme continental climate: Khangai Mountains, Mongolia |work=Proceedings, 4th Canadian Permafrost Conference |publisher=National Research Council of Canada |editor-first=H.M. |editor-last=French |pp=203–211 |url=http://pubs.aina.ucalgary.ca/cpc/CPC4-203.pdf}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last1=Swanson-Hysell |first1=Nicholas |last2=Dander |first2=Enkhbayar |date=2005 |title=A Sheet of Aufeis in the Kharkhiraa Mountains, Mongolian Altai |work=Eighteenth Annual Keck Research Symposium in Geology Proceedings |editor-last=Eberhart |editor-first=Marlene |url=http://www.keckgeology.org/files/pdf/symvol/18th/mongolia/swansonhysell.pdf}}</ref>
Analysis of satellite imagery from 2000-2015 has shown that the extent and duration of many Alaskan river icings has decreased.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Pavelsky|first=Tamlin M.|last2=Zarnetske|first2=Jay P.|date=2017-01-01|title=Rapid decline in river icings detected in Arctic Alaska: Implications for a changing hydrologic cycle and river ecosystems|url=http://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/10.1002/2016GL072397/abstract|journal=Geophysical Research Letters|volume=44|issue=7|language=en|pages=2016GL072397|doi=10.1002/2016GL072397|issn=1944-8007|bibcode=2017GeoRL..44.3228P}}</ref>
